91
00:09:08,510 --> 00:09:10,250
But how exactly do habits form?

92
00:09:10,790 --> 00:09:11,850
And why do they stick?

93
00:09:12,330 --> 00:09:15,510
The answer lies in what psychologists call the habit loop.

94
00:09:16,030 --> 00:09:20,830
This loop consists of three components, a cue, a routine, and a reward.

95
00:09:21,750 --> 00:09:26,130
The cue is a trigger that tells your brain to go into automatic mode and which habit to use.

96
00:09:26,510 --> 00:09:28,610
The routine is the behavior itself.

97
00:09:29,170 --> 00:09:34,670
The reward is what helps your brain figure out if this particular loop is worth remembering for the future.

98
00:09:35,670 --> 00:09:39,810
Understanding this loop is key to forming new habits that support delayed gratification.

99
00:09:40,430 --> 00:09:47,810
By consciously designing our cues, routines, and rewards, we can create habits that align with our long-term goals.

100
00:09:48,650 --> 00:10:02,570
For instance, if your goal is to save money, you might set up a cue, like a notification on your phone, a routine, transferring a set amount to your savings account, and a reward, tracking your progress towards a long-term financial goal.

101
00:10:03,490 --> 00:10:06,470
The power of habits lies in their ability to stick.

102
00:10:06,470 --> 00:10:12,750
